  "prompt": "Why can't someone have a cake and eat it too?",
  "response": "The phrase \"You can't have your cake and eat it too\" is a proverb meaning that one cannot simultaneously retain and consume something. It implies that you must make choices and can't enjoy the benefits of both options. If you eat the cake, you no longer have it. The expression is often used to highlight the concept of trade-offs in decisions, where gaining one thing means giving up another.",
